# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-serving
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-serving/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:model-serving/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In the field of artificial intelligence, an **inference engine** is a software component of an intelligent system that applies logical rules to the knowledge base to deduce new information.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The first inference engines were components of expert systems.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The typical expert system consisted of a knowledge base and an inference engine.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The knowledge base stored facts about the world.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The inference engine applied logical rules to the knowledge base and deduced new knowledge.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] This process would iterate as each new fact in the knowledge base could trigger additional rules in the inference engine.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Inference engines work primarily in one of two modes either special rule or facts: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Forward chaining starts with the known facts and asserts new facts.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Backward chaining starts with goals, and works backward to determine what facts must be asserted so that the goals can be achieved.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Additionally, the concept of 'inference' has expanded to include the process through which trained neural networks generate predictions or decisions.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In this context, an 'inference engine' could refer to the specific part of the system, or even the hardware, that executes these operations.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] This type of inference plays a crucial role in various applications, including (but not limited to) image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The inference phase in these applications is typically characterized by a high volume of data inputs and real-time processing requirements.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The logic that an inference engine uses is typically represented as IF-THEN rules.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The general format of such rules is IF <logical expression> THEN <logical expression>.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Prior to the development of expert systems and inference engines, artificial intelligence researchers focused on more powerful theorem prover environments that offered much fuller implementations of first-order logic.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] For example, general statements that included universal quantification (for all X some statement is true) and existential quantification (there exists some X such that some statement is true).
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] What researchers discovered is that the power of these theorem-proving environments was also their drawback.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Back in 1965, it was far too easy to create logical expressions that could take an indeterminate or even infinite time to terminate.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] For example, it is common in universal quantification to make statements over an infinite set such as the set of all natural numbers.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Such statements are perfectly reasonable and even required in mathematical proofs but when included in an automated theorem prover executing on a computer may cause the computer to fall into an infinite loop.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Focusing on IF-THEN statements (what logicians call *modus ponens*) still gave developers a very powerful general mechanism to represent logic, but one that could be used efficiently with computational resources.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] What is more, there is some psychological research that indicates humans also tend to favor IF-THEN representations when storing complex knowledge.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] A simple example of *modus ponens* often used in introductory logic books is "If you are human then you are mortal".
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] A trivial example of how this rule would be used in an inference engine is as follows.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In *forward chaining*, the inference engine would find any facts in the knowledge base that matched Human(x) and for each fact it found would add the new information Mortal(x) to the knowledge base.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] So if it found an object called Socrates that was human it would deduce that Socrates was mortal.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In *backward chaining*, the system would be given a goal, e.g. answer the question is Socrates mortal?
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] It would search through the knowledge base and determine if Socrates was human and, if so, would assert he is also mortal.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] However, in backward chaining a common technique was to integrate the inference engine with a user interface.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In that way, rather than simply being automated the system could now be interactive.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In this trivial example, if the system was given the goal to answer the question if Socrates was mortal and it didn't yet know if he was human, it would generate a window to ask the user the question "Is Socrates human?" and would then use that information accordingly.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] This innovation of integrating the inference engine with a user interface led to the second early advancement of expert systems: explanation capabilities.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The explicit representation of knowledge as rules rather than code made it possible to generate explanations to users: both explanations in real time and after the fact.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] At first these explanations were not much different than the standard debugging information that developers deal with when debugging any system.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] However, an active area of research was utilizing natural language technology to ask, understand, and generate questions and explanations using natural languages rather than computer formalisms.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] An inference engine cycles through three sequential steps: *match rules*, *select rules*, and *execute rules*.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The execution of the rules will often result in new facts or goals being added to the knowledge base, which will trigger the cycle to repeat.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] This cycle continues until no new rules can be matched.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In the first step, *match rules*, the inference engine finds all of the rules that are triggered by the current contents of the knowledge base.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In forward chaining, the engine looks for rules where the antecedent (left hand side) matches some fact in the knowledge base.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In backward chaining, the engine looks for antecedents that can satisfy one of the current goals.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In the second step, *select rules*, the inference engine prioritizes the various rules that were matched to determine the order to execute them.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] In the final step, *execute rules*, the engine executes each matched rule in the order determined in step two and then iterates back to step one again.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The cycle continues until no new rules are matched.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Early inference engines focused primarily on forward chaining.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] These systems were usually implemented in the Lisp programming language.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Lisp was a frequent platform for early AI research due to its strong capability to do symbolic manipulation.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Also, as an interpreted language it offered productive development environments appropriate to debugging complex programs.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] A necessary consequence of these benefits was that Lisp programs tended to be slower and less robust than compiled languages of the time such as C.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] A common approach in these early days was to take an expert system application and repackage the inference engine used for that system as a re-usable tool other researchers could use for the development of other expert systems.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] For example, MYCIN was an early expert system for medical diagnosis and EMYCIN was an inference engine extrapolated from MYCIN and made available for other researchers.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] As expert systems moved from research prototypes to deployed systems there was more focus on issues such as speed and robustness.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] One of the first and most popular forward chaining engines was OPS5, which used the Rete algorithm to optimize the efficiency of rule firing.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Another very popular technology that was developed was the Prolog logic programming language.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] Prolog focused primarily on backward chaining and also featured various commercial versions and optimizations for efficiency and robustness.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] As expert systems prompted significant interest from the business world, various companies, many of them started or guided by prominent AI researchers created productized versions of inference engines.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] For example, Intellicorp was initially guided by Edward Feigenbaum.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] These inference engine products were also often developed in Lisp at first.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] However, demands for more affordable and commercially viable platforms eventually made personal computer platforms very popular.
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] ClipsRules and RefPerSys (inspired by CAIA and the work of Jacques Pitrat).
[src:model-serving/inference-engine] The Frama-C static source code analyzer also uses some inference engine techniques.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:model-serving/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:model-serving/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:model-serving/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:model-serving/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:model-serving/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:model-serving/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:model-serving/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:model-serving/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:model-serving/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:model-serving/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:model-serving/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:model-serving/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:model-serving/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:model-serving/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:model-serving/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:model-serving/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:model-serving/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:model-serving/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:model-serving/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:model-serving/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:model-serving/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:model-serving/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:model-serving/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:model-serving/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:model-serving/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:model-serving/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:model-serving/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:model-serving/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:model-serving/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p02] Below are the latest statistics of the market share of all sites of the top web servers on the Internet by Netcraft.
[src:model-serving/web-server-p02] NOTE: (*) percentage rounded to integer number, because its decimal values are not publicly reported by source page (only its rounded value is reported in graph).
